<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-322-235  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 322 235.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Communications  Feb 1989 v12 n1 p3(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Performance measurement of interconnected CSMA-CD LANs. (CarrierSense Multiple Access with Collision Detection) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gee Swee Poo.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A performance measurement study of two Carrier Sense MultipleAccess with Collision Detection local area networks interconnectedby bridges and fibre optic links is considered.andP;  The network issubjected to memory-to-memory read tests with varying loads usingartificially generated traffic from personal computerworkstations.andP;  The tests span a number of configurations withvarying loadings on intranetwork and internetwork traffic.andP;  Thethroughput-delay performance of the network is quantified andanalysed.andP;  The bridge penalty is high initially, but decreases asthe load increases.andP;  The decrease can be attributed to theinterleaving effect in the bridge processing.andP;  It levels offeventually and yields a 10% overhead at the steady state.andP;  Withmixed loading of intranetwork and internetwork traffic, thebridged network shows a significant improvement in throughput anddelay in comparison with an equivalent single network connected byrepeaters.andP;  (Reprinted with permission of the publisher)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Performance MeasurementTechnologyStudyLocal Area NetworksBridges (Connector)Fiber OpticsConnectivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   Topology of two LAN segments interconnected by bridges with fiberoptic. (chart)Comparison of mean response time characteristics for allconfigurations. (graph)Comparison of total server throughput for all configurations.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>